The paper falls between "Evolution and Compression" (6.0) and "PLORA" (5.3). Its empirical sweep is more thorough than PLORA and its findings are more actionable, placing it above the reject threshold. However, the core contribution is almost entirely descriptive — no mechanistic model of why the threshold exists, no predictive framework, no novel algorithm. The "8-bit 4B" boundary is presented more strongly than the cross-benchmark evidence warrants. Missing baselines (H2O, SnapKV, KIVI) are a significant gap for a paper whose conclusions hinge on KV cache compression comparisons. The paper does not fully rule out that the threshold is architecture/benchmark specific.

Compared to "Evolution and Compression" (6.0, accepted): the current paper has a more impressive experimental scale, but the "evolution" paper addresses a more intellectually surprising phenomenon. Both are borderline papers.

